  "text": "Kubernetes and etcd implement fundamentally different approaches to leader election optimized for their respective architectures.\n\n## KUBERNETES LEASE-BASED ELECTION (kubernetes/client-go)\n\nKubernetes implements leader election through optimistic lease renewal via the Kubernetes API server. The core implementation resides in kubernetes/client-go/tools/leaderelection/, with the main engine in leaderelection.go containing the LeaderElector struct and LeaderElectionConfig.\n\nThe LeaderElector.Run() method drives the election loop, repeatedly calling tryAcquireOrRenew(). This dual-path logic implements fast-path renewal for current leaders and slow-path fallback for new candidates. The ResourceLock interface (tools/leaderelection/resourcelock/interface.go) abstracts storage backends, with LeaseLock (leaselock.go) being the preferred Kubernetes 1.14+ implementation using Lease objects.\n\nFailover handling relies on lease expiration timing. When a leader fails and stops renewing its lease within the LeaseDuration (typically 60 seconds), other candidates can acquire leadership. The LeaderCallbacks (OnStartedLeading, OnStoppedLeading, OnNewLeader) provide async notifications for state transitions. Configuration parameters—LeaseDuration (60s), RenewDeadline (15s), RetryPeriod (5s)—are tunable for different failover latency requirements. The system gracefully handles clock skew through the ratio between LeaseDuration and RenewDeadline.\n\n## ETCD RAFT-BASED ELECTION (etcd-io/raft)\n\netcd implements leader election through distributed Raft consensus voting, with the core state machine in etcd-io/raft/raft.go. The public Node interface (node.go) provides Campaign(), Tick(), and TransferLeadership() entry points. Internal election machinery includes campaign() and hup() functions that orchestrate vote requests, and state transition functions becomeLeader(), becomeFollower(), becomeCandidate(), and becomePreCandidate().\n\nElection triggering is driven by tickElection() managing election timeouts for non-leaders. The system uses randomized election timeouts within [electionTimeout, 2*electionTimeout-1] to prevent split votes when multiple nodes timeout simultaneously. The Config struct (types.go) governs election behavior through ElectionTick (timeout threshold) and HeartbeatTick (leader maintenance frequency).\n\nTwo refinements improve failover resilience. The PreVote algorithm (when Config.PreVote=true) implements a two-phase election where candidates first verify pre-election viability before incrementing the term, preventing disruption from partitioned nodes rejoining clusters. The CheckQuorum mechanism (when Config.CheckQuorum=true) causes leaders to periodically verify quorum activity, stepping down if quorum becomes inactive—preventing zombie leaders in network partitions.\n\nFailover is faster than Kubernetes: followers/candidates trigger elections within ElectionTick ticks (typically 10-50ms per tick) rather than waiting for lease expiration. The Raft algorithm ensures log safety by restricting leadership to nodes with sufficiently up-to-date logs, and uses term-based reversion where followers revert to follower state upon receiving valid leader messages with higher/equal terms.\n\n## KEY ARCHITECTURAL DIFFERENCES\n\nKubernetes favors a centralized API server as the authority, enabling tolerance of temporary cluster partitions but accepting slower failover (lease expiration latency). etcd requires peer-to-peer quorum connectivity but achieves faster failover through immediate timeout-triggered elections. Kubernetes uses optimistic lease renewal as its primary mechanism, while etcd uses consensus voting with optional pre-vote and quorum-check refinements for production deployments.\n\nBoth systems implement graceful leadership transfer: Kubernetes through the ReleaseOnCancel option in LeaderElectionConfig, and etcd through the TransferLeadership() method on the Node interface. Both track failover timing through configurable timeout parameters tuned to specific deployment needs."
}

